  • Field Details

    • balance

      private float balance
      The amount of money a Customer has in USD A float is used because double precision is not needed. The max decimal we need to represent is .99 for 99 cents

    • rate

      private static float rate
      The exchange rate for all customers. This variable is static because all Customers should share 1 rate variable

    • name

      private java.lang.String name
      Keeps the name of the Customer Main use is to label transactions, account closings and the toString method.

  • Method Details

    • exchangeValid

      private boolean exchangeValid​(float customerSWDBalance, float withdrawAMT)
      Determines whether a transaction is valid by subtracting a customers SWD balance and subtracting it by the requested withdrawal amount. Returns a boolean indicating the validity of the transaction.
      Parameters:
      customerSWDBalance - The value of the customer's balance in SWD (USD * Rate = SWD)
      withdrawAMT - The amount requested to withdraw in SWD
      Returns:
      true: transaction valid false: transaction invalid

    • displaySWD

      private static java.util.HashMap<java.lang.Integer,​java.lang.Integer> displaySWD​(float swdWithdrawalAMT)
      Takes in the requested withdrawal amount and fills a HashMap with the most minimal divisions of SWD currency to give back to the Customer. The function returns this HashMap.
      Parameters:
      swdWithdrawalAMT - The amount requested in SWD
      Returns:
      a HashMap of the individual units of SWD currency that must be given back to the Customer

    • displayUSD

      private static java.util.HashMap<java.lang.Integer,​java.lang.Integer> displayUSD​(float customerUSDBalance)
      Takes in the Customer's USD balance and fills a HashMap with the most minimal divisions of USD currency. The function returns this HashMap.
      Parameters:
      customerUSDBalance - The value of the customer's balance member variable
      Returns:
      a HashMap of the individual units of USD currency that will be displayed in deleteAccount()

    • exchangeSWD

      public java.util.HashMap<java.lang.Integer,​java.lang.Integer> exchangeSWD​(float withdrawAMT)
      Takes in the requested withdrawal amount and fills a HashMap with the most minimal divisions of SWD currency to give back to the Customer. Displays to the console the currency division breakdown. The function returns this HashMap.
      Parameters:
      withdrawAMT - The amount requested in SWD
      Returns:
      a HashMap of the individual units of SWD currency that must be given back to the Customer. The return value has no function in the driver but is used in a JUNIT test named exchangesCorrectSWD()

    • setRate

      public static void setRate​(float newRate)
      Returns nothing. Sets new rate for ALL customers. This function belongs to the definition of the Customer class.
      Parameters:
      newRate - rate to replace the old rate

    • getRate

      public static float getRate()
      Returns the current rate
      Returns:
      rate as a float value

    • setName

      public void setName​(java.lang.String name)
      Returns nothing. Sets name for the customer the function was called on.
      Parameters:
      name - rate to replace the old rate

    • getBalance

      public float getBalance()
      Returns the Customer's current balance.
      Returns:
      balance in USD as a float value.

    • deleteAccount

      public java.util.HashMap<java.lang.Integer,​java.lang.Integer> deleteAccount()
      Deletes Customer that the function was called on. "Deletion" for this program is simply returning the amount of USD left in the account. Displays to the console the currency division breakdown. The function returns this HashMap.
      Returns:
      a HashMap of the individual units of USD currency that must be given back to the Customer. The return value has no function in the driver but is used in a JUNIT test named deletesAccountReturnsCorrectUSDBalance()

    • toString

      public java.lang.String toString()
      Returns the Customer's "credentials" which include the name and balance
      Overrides:
      toString in class java.lang.Object
      Returns:
      String representing the Customer Object
